@node introduction "ARC - Introduction"
@next "installation"

Ooooh. I hate messy introductions.

(Lights fade)

(people shuffle in their seats)

(curtains open)

It's ARC!

(wild applause?)


 This is the second release of Adam's Recipe Companion. I first got the
idea when I got A CU Amiga CD with a snippet of LSD CD 3 on it. There
were a few files containing absolutely LOADS of recipes. Being a bit of
a cook and all that, I bought the LSD3 CD and ended up with over 4 megs
of the blighters.

With no way to look through them, and no software supplied on the CD,
and with a copy of Blitz Basic sitting on the shelf in the shop, I thought
it would be fun and funky to write a program to help sort them out.

Oh, and there was absolutely bugger all recipe software for the Amiga.
And those "No Amiga To Waste" people wanted one. 

Turned out to be quite a lot of fun, and a little challenging. Respect to
Blitz is due.

So. Here it is. Enjoy.

Adam

@endnode

@node installation "Installing ARC"
@next "changes"

Just copy it to anywhere.

ARC isn't fussy. It just likes a nice warm lap to sleep on now and again.
The recipe files are accessed via a file requestor, so I'd recommend
you keep them in the same directory to avoid too much navigating around.

Oh, aye. You'll need opal.font and opal/9 in your FONTS: directory.
I like it. And no-one has emailed me to indicate any different. So there.
(Not that anyone has emailed me *at all*, but there you go. I hope someone
is getting these hints.)
@endnode

@node usage "How to use ARC"

Try it. It's easy.

When ARC starts, it will present you with a requester box. Select your
desired recipe file (not the .qwk ones...) and ARC will attempt to load it.
You will then be presented with a list of the recipes in the file. You
can double click on one to view it if you like.

ARC will load in MenuMaster exported recipes, as that appears to be the
commonest format I can find.

Menus
~~~~~

Load - loads a new file

Search - searches under category

Quit - quits (clever, that)

Makeqwk - makes a .qwk file - Use to speed up searches in future - it
builds a reference database, y'see.

Delete - deletes tagged recipes. Actually exports non-tagged recipes and
copies over the original file. No-one said ARC was well-written...

Export - Exports recipes to a new file. Will append to the file, so you
can build up your own personal database if you like. You can sort an
existing database by tagging all recipes and exporting them.

Buttons
~~~~~~~

Back - Goes back to previous screen

Print - prints the recipe. Will *only* print recipes, not whole menus.
Tag/Untag - Tags/untags the last recipe selected, or the recipe shown
Tag/untag all - Tags or untags all recipes.

The tags are used for printing, exporting or deleting. Any further
suggestions are welcome...

Now wasn't that hard.

There's even some @{"Keyboard Shortcuts" link shortcuts} if you dislike mice


@endnode

@node shortcuts "Keyboard Shortcuts"
@next changes

  K E Y B O A R D   S H O R T C U T S

Hey, doncha just *hate* mice? Move, click, move, move click. click, move.
Yuck.

With that in mind, ARC has lots of lovely shortcuts.

Menu Commands:
Press the Right Amiga button along with the indicated key to select
a menu item. As per every other Amiga application.

Right Amiga +
L = Load
S = Search
Q = Quit
X = Export tagged recipes
D = Delete tagged recipes
P = Print tagged recipes

Button Substitutes

Backspace/Escape = back to menu from recipe
t = tag highlighted recipe
up/down cursors = move highlight bar, or jump to previous/next recipe.
Return/enter = view highlighted recipe.

The more observant among you will notice that you can quickly browse through
the recipes, tagging ones to delete (or print, or export) as you go. Now
isn't that nice.

@endnode

@node changes "Changes since release 1"
@next "author"

So, what has changed in ARC since the last release.

Well...

1. Now uses opal.font rather than topaz. Word wraps on the fly to make
sure that it looks cool. Much better.

2. .qwk file support. This *seriously* speeds up searches. Just do
a search as normal, then hit the makeqwk menu button to save a .qwk file.
The search routine builds an internal database, and this function exports it
so you don't have to wait next time around.

3. Tagging - thought it would be nice to print more than one recipe at once.
Once tagging was done, feeping creaturism demanded deletion and exporting...

4. Change from freeware to email-ware. I've had the grand total of *one*
email regarding ARC. I'd like a little more feedback, please. Just a
quick note to say "Hi, I've tried ARC" will do.

5. A few new recipes added to the archive. Hey, people! Why not upload
some of your own!

6. @{"Keyboard shortcuts" link shortcuts}. Hey, I hate using the mouse.

@endnode

